Before reaching the point of a lawsuit, Zirkel (2007) notes that mediation and a resolution session are the appropriate steps to address, and hopefully resolve, disputes related to identifying a disability, evaluating a child, or the placement of a child with a disability. If these steps do not resolve the dispute, a due process hearing may be scheduled. In the event that the due process hearing does not bring resolution, the decision from the hearing, which is binding, can be appealed to the State Education Agency (SEA) if the SEA did not conduct the hearing. If these steps are not sufficient to resolve the dispute, the decision may be appealed—by bringing civil action in state or federal court (Procedural Safeguards, n.d.). Civil actions may include class action lawsuits, which is defined by the Federal Rules of Civil Procedure as follows:

One or more members of a class may sue or be sued as representative parties on behalf only if:

(1) the class is so numerous that joinder of all members is impracticable;

(2) there are questions of law or fact that are common to the class;

(3) the claims or defenses of the representative parties are typical of the claims or defenses of the class;

(4) the representative parties will fairly and adequately protect the interests of the class. (Federal Rules of Civil Procedures, 2007, p. 27)
